<h2>Event in May 2020</h2>
<h3> Cold nights and snowfall in May </h3>
<br><br>
An extensive cold spell passed over large parts of Europe during 11-15
May. This period is known as the Ice Saints and is feared since a long
time, because of the frost damage in the late spring season. Western
and Central Europe were affected by this cold spell with a temperature
drop of 20 degrees within one day. Snow came to Eastern Europe,
particularly to Poland, the Baltic countries, Belarus and northern
European Russia. Parts of Northern Europe recorded heavy snowfall on
10-12 May, e.g. in Troms&#246; (northern Norway), and snowfall was
even reported for places in southern Norway down to 200-300m
altitude. Furthermore, parts of Scotland and the northern Alpine
region down to 500m altitude locally were hit by snow. The last time
when snow fell in northern Switzerland in middle altitudes
(e.g. St. Gallen, 800m) was in winter 1994/95.
<br><br>
On 13 May there was a front passage in Western Europe (Figure 1),
bringing maritime air to the Low Countries. The wind turned from south
to north and during the front passage heavy showers occurred. Details
of the wind up to 200m are shown in Figure 2. Southern Germany
(Bavaria) had below freezing temperatures, for example -2.6&#176;C in
N&#252;rnberg on 12 May, and also further west in France (-0.7&#176;C in
Epinal, Vosges) on the same day, and in the Netherlands (-1.2&#176;C
in De Bilt) on 14 and 15 May. Two or more frost nights after 10 May in
De Bilt are rare; the last year when this occurred was 1973.
<br><br>
