<h2>The weather in May 2020</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
Over central, northern and northeastern Europe the average
temperatures in May 2020 were lower than the 1981-2010 average for
May, especially over Eastern Europe and Norway where largest negative
anomalies (up to -3&deg;C) occurred for mean temperature, but also for
maximum temperature (Figure 7). Compared with the climatological
period of 1981-2010 these temperatures were 'much below' or even
'exceptionally below' average (Figure 8). Over western and southern
parts of Europe, on the contrary, the average temperatures in May were
higher than the 1981-2010 average for May, with 'exceptionally above
average' mean as well as minimum and maximum temperatures occurring
over Iberia, large parts of France and also over the UK. Largest
anomalies occurred over Iberia with values of +4&deg;C and more above
normal (Figures 7 and 8). When averaged over Europe as a whole,
positive and negative anomalies almost cancelled out, resulting in an
European-average temperature which was only 0.4&deg;C above the
1981-2010 normal (Figure 11).
