<strong>Evolution of the European land-surface temperature</strong>
<br><br>
Figure 11 (left panel) shows the European-averaged temperature from 1950 onward, where blue bars show temperatures which are below the 1981-2010 average and red bars above this mean value. The green bar is the provisional 2020 estimate, based on data until the end of May and climatological means for the remaining months. The grey bars in the panel indicate the estimated uncertainties which take into account the errors introduced by spatial interpolation over areas without observation stations, inhomogeneities in the temperature data that result from station relocations / changes in measurement instruments etc., and biases due to urbanisation, as documented in Van der Schrier et al. (2013) and Chrysanthou et al. (2014). The uncertainties tell us that although we are not 100% certain about the ranking of individual years, the overall positive trend since the 1980s is very pronounced.
<br><br>
The right panel of Figure 11 shows the daily temperature, averaged over Europe, for the past 12 months.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/may2020/EuropeanAverage_annual_wrt81-10_202005_v20.0e.png"><img alt="" src="../images/may2020/EuropeanAverage_annual_wrt81-10_202005_v20.0e.png" width="250px"></a>
<a href="../images/may2020/dailyanomalies_0.25deg_202005_v20.0e.png"><img alt="" src="../images/may2020/dailyanomalies_0.25deg_202005_v20.0e.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 11: European land surface temperature: annual anomalies with the current year in green. The grey bands show the uncertainty in the averaged temperature (left). Daily anomalies with respect to the seasonal cycle until the end of May 2020 (right). (Based on E-OBS)</em>
<br><br>
<h3>Precipitation</h3>
<br><br>
Over western and northern Europe, the dry conditions present already in April continued in May due to an extended period of high pressure centred close to the British Isles. Precipitation sums were 'exceptionally below' normal over parts of the UK and the Benelux countries (Figure 13). England saw its driest May on record and Wales its second driest. In Belgium, the station of Ukkel reported for May only 5.4 mm while the climatological mean for May is 66.5 mm. For the months of April and May together, the precipitation deficit reached almost 100mm, which is the largest since 1893. Also the Netherlands experienced their driest spring on record: End of May the precipitation deficit for spring (the sum of the daily differences between potential evaporation and precipitation since 1 April) summed up to 161 mm. Accordingly, the northwestern part of Europe is one of the regions sticking out with 'exceptionally below average' precipitation amounts for the spring season as a whole as seen in Figure 15.
Wetter conditions occurred in May particularly over eastern Europe and parts of southeastern Europe as well as over Spain with "exceptionally above average" precipitation sums over Ukraine and neighbouring parts of Russia (Figure 13). The northeastern region had its second wettest May since 1951 (Figure 14).
<br><br>
